@node "Intro" "Introduktion"
                          @{apen 2}@{b}INTRODUCTION@{ub}@{apen 1}

If you want the version information to be presented in
a requester, or if you think than c:version doesn't find all
version strings, this program is for you. Instead of
like c:version just tell the version and revision number
by default, VersionWB always tells you all it could find.

VersionWB may completely replace AmigaDos version. You may rename
VersionWB to version.

VersionWB have these features:

* It will bring up a requester with the version information.

* It support several files in the command line parameter template.

* You can shift-doubleclick an icon with VersionWB and
  then get all that version stuff.

* You may also pick the file you want to know the version number of
  by using a file requester.

* It will find version strings in WB1.3 libraries and devices,
  c:version does not, e.g. narrator.device.

* If you use it with ToolManager you can have an appicon in
  your Workbench. Drop the icon on the appicon, and the
  version information will be presented (if the file contains a
  version string :-)

* It also has an optional text output.

* It recognizes any packed file (uses xfdmaster.library).

* All other features which AmigaDos Version has, as far as I know 8-).

* Can be opened on a publicscreen

* Can set the filenote of files to there versioninfo.

* Can set the filedate to the one found in the version string

* Finds even files in your shell-path
 
@endnode

@node "requi" 

VersionWB requires:

Kickstart 2.04+ (WB v37).
An Amiga, not that kind of computer which have mess-dos in it :-).
Any Amiga compatible computer will work, eg. Draco.

XfdMaster.library v. 37+ is required to be able to find version
info in packed files: Aminet:util/pack/XFDxxx.lha

@endnode

@node "Usage"
			   @{apen 2}@{b}Usage@{ub}@{apen 1}

@{b}If to use it from Workbench:@{ub}

Shift-doubleclick an icon with VersionWB and
then get all that version stuff. Multi selection
does work.  

If no icon is selected, a file requester will appear.

@{b}ToolTypes:@{ub}
MAX=number of characters
PUBSCREEN=screen
NOXFD
FILE
RES
REQPATH=directory-path which the file requester starts with. 

For description see below.

@{"Use it with ToolManager" link "tips"}

@{b}If to use it from Shell:@{ub}

The command line is:

VersionWb [libraryname, devicename or filename]/[*]/[HELP]/[TEXT][MAX}/[FULL]/[FILE]/[RES]
[VERSION]/[REVISION]/[PUBSCREEN]/[COMFILE]/[COMDROPNAME]/[COMERASE]/[QUIET]/[NOXFD]/
[REQ]/[NOMISC]/[SETDATE]/[COMMENT]
template: NAME/[M],*/S,HELP/S,TEXT/S,FULL/S,FILE/S,RES/S,VERSION/N,REVISION/N,MAX/N,
PUBSCREEN/N,COMFILE/S,COMDROPNAME/S,COMERASE/S,QUIET/S,NOXFD/S,REQ/S,NOMISC/S,COMMENT/S,SETDATE/S
@{b}NAME@{ub} 
     For example 'VersionWB asl.library' will give the version
     of the currently installed asl.library (resident in memory).
     You can load several files
     at once, e.g. 'VersionWB asl.library mcpgfx.library' or
	'VersionWB SYS:utilities/multiview SYS:utilities/more'.
	If you run VersionWB with for instance VersionWB asl.library and the
	current directory is LIBS: you will get the version info from the local
	file and the resident file in memory.
	
@{b}*@{ub}
     Type in 'VersionWb *' if you want a file requester to appear,
     where you can pick the file you want to know the version number
     of.

@{b}HELP@{ub}
     Type in 'VersionWb HELP' to get some help.
		
@{b}TEXT@{ub}       
     If you want a text output instead of a requester.

@{b}MAX@{ub}  To set the maximum width of the requester, in number
     of characters. Default is 50 characters.

@{b}To set the width of the requester@{ub}

The environmental variable VERSIONWB_MAX sets the
maximum width of the "file" and "misc" field in chars.
The cutting method is word oriented.

Set it in Shell with SETENV VERSIONWB_MAX <maxchars>
You just have to do this once if you copy the file ENV:VersionWB_Max to ENVARC:
For example: SetEnv VERSIONWB_MAX 35
             Copy ENV:VERSIONWB_MAX ENVARC:

@{b}FULL@{ub} is the same as TEXT except for that just one (or two) lines is used
(like c:version). This is used if you want the same output as c:version.

@{b}FILE@{ub} File is not resident. It is there for ability to replace c:version.

@{b}RES@{ub} File is resident. This is default. (not if  the file can be
             found in the current directory. Se above, FILE.

@{b}VERSION@{ub} Accepts a numeric argument.  If the version of the 
        library or device in question is lower than this 
        argument, the return code will be set to WARN.
        TEXT is set. E.g. VersionWB asl.library 40 6   (version 40 and revision 6)

@{b}REVISION@{ub} Like VERSION, but checks the revision number of the 
        specified library or device.
        TEXT is set.

@{b}UNIT@{ub} No usage yet ...

@{b}PUBSCREEN@{ub} Accepts a name of a public screen as argument. 

@{b}COMFILE Inserts@{ub} the version string as filenote.

     @{b}COMDROPNAME@{ub} Used with COMFILE. The filename is not inserted.
     @{b}COMERASE@{ub} Used with COMFILE. The version string will
                       replace the old filenote.

@{b}QUIET@{ub} Same es >NIL:. Don't show requester or text output.

@{b}NOXFD@{ub} Prevent VersionWB to open xfdmaster.library. May be useful
               if you don't have enough memory ...

@{b}REQ@{ub} Show a requester. The opposite of TEXT.

@{b}NOMISC@{ub} Do not output the misc:-info.

@{b}COMMENT@{ub} Comment file with versionnumber & date.

@{b}SETDATE@{ub} Set the file's date to the one found in version string.

@{b}NO KEYWORD@{ub} then you get some system info. Workbench, Kickstart, MUI
and CyperGfx version.

@{b}NEW!@{ub}You can now set default command line parameters with the
environmental variable VERSIONWB_PARAM.
e.g. Setenv VersionWB_param "TEXT FULL" will give you text outputs like AmigaDos
Version when started from CLI and show a requester when started from Workbench.
This could give problems with file managers (e.g DOpus), then use REQ which
will force VersionWB to show requesters. ( e.g. VersionWB {f} REQ )

@{b}NEW!@{ub} VersionWB now automatically tries your shell-paths if the file does
not exist in the current dirctory, LIBS: or DEVS.

@endnode

@node "messages"
                          @{apen 2}@{b}MESSAGES@{ub}@{apen 1}

Some messages may appear in the requster:
'Smart version string search used!' This means that VersionWB has made what it could
to find the right version string. The information in requester may be false, but usually
is true.

'Packed with xxxx' VersionWB has recognized a packed file.

'Info from resident file' Info comes from a file which is resident in memory.

@endnode
